{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "These dense matrices often contain small but storage-intensive values that have minimal impact on GNN aggregation performance.",
    "Moreover, certain application scenarios, such as molecular graphs, require binary and discrete adjacency matrices for downstream tasks.",
    "Hence, it becomes essential to sparsify the generated adjacency matrices, and numerous sparsification methods have been proposed to tackle these challenges.",
    "For instance, GCond [26] utilizes the threshold to remove the entries with small values and justifies that suitable choices of threshold do not degrade performance but increase the scalability of the condensed graph.",
    "SGDD [31] employs the L2 norm of the adjacency matrix as a regularization term for sparsity control."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "For instance, GCond [26] utilizes the threshold to remove the entries with small values and justifies that suitable choices of threshold do not degrade performance but increase the scalability of the condensed graph.",
    "SGDD [31] employs the L2 norm of the adjacency matrix as a regularization term for sparsity control."
